{"id":"1412.1168","submitter":"Chengbo Zhu","authors":"Chengbo Zhu and Xiaolin Wang","title":"Tuning the conductance of H$_{2}$O@C$_{60}$ by position of the\n  encapsulated H$_{2}$O","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The change of conductance of single molecule junctions in response to various\nexternal stimuli is the fundamental mechanism for single-molecule electronic\ndevices with multiple functionalities. We propose a concept that the\nconductance of molecule systems can be tuned from its inside. The conductance\nis varied in C$_{60}$ with encapsulated H$_{2}$O, H$_{2}$O@C$_{60}$. The\ntransport properties of the H$_{2}$O@C$_{60}$-based nanostructure sandwiched\nbetween electrodes are studied using first-principles calculations based on the\nnon-equilibrium Green's function formalism. Our results show that the\nconductance of the H$_{2}$O@C$_{60}$ is sensitive to the position of the\nH$_{2}$O and its dipole direction inside the cage with changes in conductance\nup to 20%. Our study paves a way for the H$_{2}$O@C$_{60}$ molecule to be a new\nplatform for novel molecule based electronics and sensors.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Dec 2014 03:24:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-12-04"}
